1. Definition
                
                RDD (Resilient Distributed Dataset) is PySparkâ€™s core data structure, representing an immutable, distributed collection of objects.
                
                It is logically partitioned, allowing processing across multiple cluster nodes.
                
                Can store any type of object â€” Python, Java, Scala, or user-defined classes.
                
                Enables fast and efficient MapReduce-style computations.
                
                Formally defined as a read-only, partitioned collection of records created via deterministic operations.


2. Key Features of RDD
Feature	Description
                  Resilient	Fault-tolerant â€” can recover data automatically after node failure.
                  Distributed	Operates across multiple cluster nodes for parallel computation.
                  Dataset	Represents partitioned data collections such as lists, tables, or tuples.


3. Benefits of RDD

                    âœ… Fault Tolerance: Automatically rebuilds lost partitions using lineage.
                    
                    âš™ï¸ Parallel Processing: Splits data across partitions for simultaneous execution.
                    
                    ğŸ”„ Flexibility: Supports structured, semi-structured, and unstructured data.
                    
                    ğŸ”’ Immutability: Ensures data consistency by preventing modification.
                    
                    ğŸ§  Lazy Evaluation: Delays execution until an action is triggered, allowing Spark to optimize performance.

4. Limitations of RDD

Limitation	                                       Explanation
Lack of Schema	                              Not ideal for structured data; lacks built-in schema support.
Verbose Code                                	Requires detailed, low-level programming (map, filter, reduce).
No Query Optimization                       	Doesnâ€™t use Catalyst Optimizer â€” slower than DataFrames/Datasets.
Higher Memory Use	                            Less efficient memory management compared to DataFrames.
Steeper Learning Curve	                      Needs deeper understanding of Spark internals and functional programming.


